head on, providing scholars with thoughtful and often practical answers to their many methodological concerns. These original essays range from how to conduct research on youth in ways that can be empowering for them, to issues of writing and representation, to respecting boundaries and to dealing with issues of risk and responsibility to those interviewed. For anyone doing research or working with children and young adults, Representing Youth offers an indispensable guide to many of the unique dilemmas that research with kids entails.Contributors include: Amy L. Best, Sari Knopp Biklen, Elizabeth Chin, Susan Driver, Marc Flacks, Kathryn Gold Hadley, Madeline Leonard, C.J. Pascoe, Rebecca Raby, Alyssa Richman, Jessica Taft, Michael Ungar, Yvonne Vissing, and Stephani Etheridge Woodson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildrenxResearch. 0aChildrenxStudy and teaching. 0aYouthxResearch. 0aYouthxStudy and teaching. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh  aThese.  aboundaries.  aconduct.  adealing.  aempowering.  aessays.  afrom.  ainterviewed.  aissues.  aoriginal.  arange.  arepresentation.  aresearch.  arespecting.  aresponsibility.  arisk.  athat.  athem.  athose.  aways.  awith.  awriting.  ayouth.1 aBest, Amy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBest, Amy L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDriver, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtheridge Woodson, Stephani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlacks, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGold Hadley, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab